{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "AqueousEquilibrationTimescale",
        "description": "Characteristic timescale for a gas to equilibrate with aqueous aerosol particles — Seinfeld & Pandis (2006), Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics, 2nd ed., Chapter 12, Eq. 12.147. The aqueous equilibration timescale τ_a is the solid-particle equilibration timescale τ_s scaled by the dimensionless buffering factor m_w/K_A, where m_w is the aerosol water mass concentration and K_A is an equilibrium constant. The factor accounts for the additional buffering effect of Henry's-law dissolution of the gas into the aerosol aqueous phase: a larger aqueous reservoir m_w relative to K_A lengthens the time to reach equilibrium. Migrated from Aerosol.jl AqueousEquilibrationTimescale.",
        "tags": [
            "aerosol",
            "seinfeld_pandis_ch12",
            "timescales",
            "mass-transfer"
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "AqueousEquilibrationTimescale": {
            "reference": {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., and Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd Edition, John Wiley & Sons, Chapter 12. Aqueous equilibration timescale: Eq. 12.147.",
                "notes": "source_ref: Aerosol.jl@c8c640bb636b22f2425460e9ed5cba50793bfee1:src/timescales.jl:183\n\nUpstream `AqueousEquilibrationTimescale` is an MTK `@component` (no parameterization). It declares three scalar `@parameters` — `m_w` (aerosol water mass concentration, kg/m^3), `K_A` (equilibrium constant, kg/m^3), `τ_s` (solid-particle equilibration timescale, s) — and one scalar `@variable` `τ_a` (aqueous equilibration timescale, s). The single equation is `τ_a ~ (m_w / K_A) * τ_s` — Eq. 12.147 of Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Ch. 12: the aqueous equilibration timescale is the solid-particle timescale `τ_s` scaled by the dimensionless buffering factor `m_w / K_A`.\n\nτ_s as a parameter: in this isolated component `τ_s` is a free input `@parameter` (default 1.0 s). Physically it is the output of the sibling `SolidEquilibrationTimescale` component (same file, src/timescales.jl:145); the gas-equilibration timescale chain solid → aqueous would be wired by coupling, but each component is migrated standalone, so `τ_s` is carried verbatim as the upstream `@parameter`.\n\nObserved classification: AqueousEquilibrationTimescale has no `D()` time-derivative anywhere — it is a purely-algebraic component. `τ_a` is an algebraic output (`τ_a ~ (m_w/K_A)·τ_s`). After MTK `mtkcompile` / `structural_simplify` the compiled system has zero ODE states and `τ_a` becomes an observed quantity. It is therefore serialized as `type: observed` with an `expression` (not `type: state` with an equation), and the `equations` array is empty, matching the sibling pure-algebraic Aerosol.jl migrations `zsr.esm` and `critical_ssa.esm`.\n\nUnicode identifiers `τ_s` and `τ_a` are kept verbatim from the upstream `@parameters` / `@variables` declarations; the ESM identifier pattern permits unicode and the sibling Aerosol.jl migrations (`zsr.esm`: `α_w`; `kelvin.esm`: `σ`, `ρ_l`) keep Greek symbols, so no ASCII rename is applied.\n\nTests authored from physics: the upstream `timescales.jl` carries no test file (`has_tests: N` in the migration tracker). The inline `tests` block is authored from the closed-form Eq. 12.147 — pinning the exact analytic value of `τ_a = (m_w/K_A)·τ_s` at the upstream default parameterization, at the buffering-factor crossover `m_w = K_A` (where `τ_a = τ_s`), in the strong-buffering regime `m_w ≫ K_A`, and exercising the linear dependence on `m_w` and `τ_s` and the inverse dependence on `K_A`.\n\nNot migrated: `timescales.jl` defines six independent `@component`s — `GasDiffusionTimescale`, `AqueousDiffusionTimescale`, `InterfacialTimescale`, `ReactionTimescale`, `SolidEquilibrationTimescale`, and `AqueousEquilibrationTimescale`. Only `AqueousEquilibrationTimescale` (src/timescales.jl:183) is in scope for this component migration; the other five are separate migration-tracker rows with their own target `.esm` files under `components/aerosol/timescales/`.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-8): the model is a single closed-form algebraic expression — one division and one multiplication — so float64 evaluation roundoff is at the 1-ULP (~1e-16 relative) level; rel=1e-8 leaves ample headroom. The `zero_water_zero_timescale` test adds a tight per-assertion abs=1e-20 so a stuck-nonzero regression in the `τ_a` product cannot pass on the relative branch."
            },
            "variables": {
                "m_w": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/m^3",
                    "default": 1.0e-8,
                    "description": "Aerosol water mass concentration — the mass of liquid water in the aerosol aqueous phase per unit volume of air (Eq. 12.147 term m_w). Sets the size of the aqueous reservoir the gas must fill to reach equilibrium."
                },
                "K_A": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/m^3",
                    "default": 1.0e-3,
                    "description": "Equilibrium constant (Eq. 12.147 term K_A) — sets the denominator of the dimensionless buffering factor m_w/K_A. A larger K_A weakens the Henry's-law buffering and shortens the aqueous equilibration timescale."
                },
                "τ_s": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "s",
                    "default": 1.0,
                    "description": "Solid-particle equilibration timescale (Eq. 12.147 term τ_s) — the characteristic time for the gas to equilibrate with solid aerosol particles. A free input parameter here; physically the output of the sibling SolidEquilibrationTimescale component."
                },
                "τ_a": {
                    "type": "observed",
                    "units": "s",
                    "description": "Aqueous equilibration timescale (Eq. 12.147): τ_a = (m_w/K_A)·τ_s. The characteristic time for the gas to equilibrate with aqueous aerosol particles, equal to the solid-particle timescale τ_s scaled by the dimensionless buffering factor m_w/K_A. A larger aqueous reservoir relative to K_A lengthens the equilibration time.",
                    "expression": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "/",
                                "args": [
                                    "m_w",
                                    "K_A"
                                ]
                            },
                            "τ_s"
                        ]
                    }
                }
            },
            "equations": [],
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-08
            },
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "default_parameters",
                    "description": "Eq. 12.147 at the upstream default parameterization (m_w = 1e-8 kg/m³, K_A = 1e-3 kg/m³, τ_s = 1.0 s). The buffering factor m_w/K_A = 1e-5 scales the solid-particle timescale to τ_a = (1e-8/1e-3)·1.0 = 1e-5 s — aqueous equilibration is far faster than solid because the aerosol-regime water reservoir is small relative to K_A. The output is algebraic and time-invariant, so the same value is asserted at t = 0 and t = 1.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {},
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "τ_a",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1.0e-5
                        },
                        {
                            "variable": "τ_a",
                            "time": 1.0,
                            "expected": 1.0e-5
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "buffering_factor_unity",
                    "description": "At the buffering-factor crossover m_w = K_A the dimensionless factor m_w/K_A = 1 and the aqueous equilibration timescale equals the solid-particle timescale exactly: τ_a = (1e-3/1e-3)·1.0 = 1.0 s. This is the transition between the fast-aqueous regime (m_w < K_A) and the slow-aqueous regime (m_w > K_A).",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "m_w": 1.0e-3
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "τ_a",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1.0
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "strong_buffering_amplification",
                    "description": "In the strong-buffering regime m_w ≫ K_A the aqueous reservoir is large and equilibration is much slower than the solid case. With m_w = 1e-2 kg/m³ (a cloud-scale liquid-water content) and K_A = 1e-3 kg/m³, the buffering factor m_w/K_A = 10 amplifies the solid timescale to τ_a = 10·1.0 = 10.0 s.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "m_w": 1.0e-2
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "τ_a",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 10.0
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "linear_in_water_mass",
                    "description": "Eq. 12.147 is linear in the aerosol water mass concentration m_w. Doubling m_w from the 1e-8 default to 2e-8 kg/m³ doubles the aqueous equilibration timescale from 1e-5 to τ_a = (2e-8/1e-3)·1.0 = 2e-5 s — a larger aqueous reservoir takes proportionally longer to fill.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "m_w": 2.0e-8
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "τ_a",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 2.0e-5
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "inverse_in_equilibrium_constant",
                    "description": "Eq. 12.147 varies inversely with the equilibrium constant K_A. Doubling K_A from the 1e-3 default to 2e-3 kg/m³ halves the aqueous equilibration timescale from 1e-5 to τ_a = (1e-8/2e-3)·1.0 = 5e-6 s — a larger K_A weakens the Henry's-law buffering.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "K_A": 2.0e-3
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "τ_a",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 5.0e-6
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "linear_in_solid_timescale",
                    "description": "Eq. 12.147 scales linearly with the solid-particle equilibration timescale τ_s — the buffering factor m_w/K_A multiplies it directly. Raising τ_s tenfold from 1.0 to 10.0 s raises the aqueous timescale tenfold to τ_a = (1e-8/1e-3)·10.0 = 1e-4 s.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "τ_s": 10.0
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "τ_a",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1.0e-4
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "zero_water_zero_timescale",
                    "description": "Limiting case: with no aerosol aqueous phase (m_w = 0) the buffering factor m_w/K_A vanishes and τ_a = 0 exactly — there is no aqueous reservoir for the gas to equilibrate with. A tight per-assertion absolute tolerance guards against a stuck-nonzero regression in the τ_a product.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "m_w": 0.0
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "τ_a",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 0.0,
                            "tolerance": {
                                "abs": 1e-20
                            }
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ],
            "examples": [
                {
                    "id": "timescale_vs_water_mass",
                    "description": "The aqueous equilibration timescale rises linearly with the aerosol water mass concentration (Eq. 12.147). Sweeping m_w over the 1e-9–1e-3 kg/m³ range — from a dilute aerosol-water loading up to a cloud-scale liquid-water content — at the default K_A = 1e-3 kg/m³ and τ_s = 1.0 s traces the line τ_a = (m_w/K_A)·τ_s; τ_a reaches τ_s as m_w approaches K_A.",
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "m_w",
                                "range": {
                                    "start": 1.0e-9,
                                    "stop": 1.0e-3,
                                    "count": 60,
                                    "scale": "log"
                                }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "tau_a_vs_m_w",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Aqueous equilibration timescale τ_a as a function of aerosol water mass concentration m_w (at the default K_A and τ_s).",
                            "x": {
                                "variable": "m_w",
                                "label": "Aerosol water mass concentration m_w (kg/m³)"
                            },
                            "y": {
                                "variable": "τ_a",
                                "label": "Aqueous equilibration timescale τ_a (s)"
                            }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "timescale_vs_equilibrium_constant",
                    "description": "The aqueous equilibration timescale varies inversely with the equilibrium constant (Eq. 12.147). With m_w and τ_s at their defaults, sweeping K_A over the 1e-4–1e-1 kg/m³ range traces the τ_a = (m_w/K_A)·τ_s hyperbola — a larger K_A weakens the Henry's-law buffering and shortens the equilibration time.",
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "K_A",
                                "range": {
                                    "start": 1.0e-4,
                                    "stop": 1.0e-1,
                                    "count": 60,
                                    "scale": "log"
                                }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "tau_a_vs_K_A",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Aqueous equilibration timescale τ_a as a function of the equilibrium constant K_A (at the default m_w and τ_s).",
                            "x": {
                                "variable": "K_A",
                                "label": "Equilibrium constant K_A (kg/m³)"
                            },
                            "y": {
                                "variable": "τ_a",
                                "label": "Aqueous equilibration timescale τ_a (s)"
                            }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "timescale_water_mass_equilibrium_constant_heatmap",
                    "description": "Joint dependence of the aqueous equilibration timescale on the aerosol water mass concentration and the equilibrium constant (Eq. 12.147). The heatmap of τ_a(m_w, K_A) at the default τ_s = 1.0 s shows the timescale rising with the aqueous reservoir m_w and falling with K_A — the buffering-factor m_w/K_A surface.",
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "m_w",
                                "range": {
                                    "start": 1.0e-9,
                                    "stop": 1.0e-3,
                                    "count": 30,
                                    "scale": "log"
                                }
                            },
                            {
                                "parameter": "K_A",
                                "range": {
                                    "start": 1.0e-4,
                                    "stop": 1.0e-1,
                                    "count": 25,
                                    "scale": "log"
                                }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "tau_a_m_w_K_A_heatmap",
                            "type": "heatmap",
                            "description": "τ_a(m_w, K_A) heatmap at the default solid-particle timescale τ_s = 1.0 s.",
                            "x": {
                                "variable": "m_w",
                                "label": "Aerosol water mass concentration m_w (kg/m³)"
                            },
                            "y": {
                                "variable": "K_A",
                                "label": "Equilibrium constant K_A (kg/m³)"
                            },
                            "value": {
                                "variable": "τ_a",
                                "reduce": "final"
                            }
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        }
    }
}
